7
00:00:14,969 --> 00:00:17,210
the reason why the British gave Hong Kong

8
00:00:17,210 --> 00:00:20,070
back to China those 20 years ago.

9
00:00:20,070 --> 00:00:22,340
Hong Kong today is under a weird policy

10
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:24,780
called “One Country, Two Systems,”

11
00:00:24,780 --> 00:00:26,830
where even though it’s part of China,

12
00:00:26,830 --> 00:00:28,640
it’s governed separately.

13
00:00:28,640 --> 00:00:29,830
Mostly.

14
00:00:29,830 --> 00:00:31,190
So you have freedoms in Hong Kong

15
00:00:31,190 --> 00:00:33,239
that could land you in a labor camp

16
00:00:33,239 --> 00:00:35,350
in the rest of China.

17
00:00:35,350 --> 00:00:37,499
So why does the People’s Republic of China

18
00:00:37,499 --> 00:00:39,199
have these two contradictory

19
00:00:39,199 --> 00:00:40,899
systems of government?

20
00:00:40,899 --> 00:00:42,819
And why did Great Britain give Hong Kong

21
00:00:42,819 --> 00:00:45,070
back to China in the first place?

22
00:00:45,070 --> 00:00:47,539
Well, once upon a time,

23
00:00:47,539 --> 00:00:50,739
everyone wanted stuff that was made in China.

24
00:00:50,739 --> 00:00:54,620
Because no one made better quality stuff than
China.

25
00:00:54,620 --> 00:00:56,210
But China didn't really want

26
00:00:56,210 --> 00:00:57,409
any of the cheap junk

27
00:00:57,409 --> 00:00:59,079
made by other countries,

28
00:00:59,079 --> 00:01:01,149
like say, Great Britain.

29
00:01:01,149 --> 00:01:02,629
Which sucked for them.

30
00:01:02,629 --> 00:01:04,780
But then, in the early 1800s,

31
00:01:04,780 --> 00:01:06,460
the British figured out something

32
00:01:06,460 --> 00:01:08,060
everyone wanted:

33
00:01:08,060 --> 00:01:09,060
drugs.

34
00:01:09,060 --> 00:01:10,950
Specifically, opium.

35
00:01:10,950 --> 00:01:13,220
The Chinese tried to just say no to drugs

36
00:01:13,220 --> 00:01:16,500
